Certainly! To generate a table of contents automatically in a LaTeX document, you need to use the `\tableofcontents` command at the point where you want the table of contents to appear. LaTeX will automatically collect all the chapter, section, subsection, etc., headings, along with their page numbers, and list them in the table of contents.

Here is a simple example of a LaTeX document that includes a table of contents:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents % This command generates the table of contents

\newpage % Start a new page after the table of contents

\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction of the document.

\subsection{Background}
This subsection provides background information.

\subsection{Scope}
This subsection discusses the scope of the document.

\section{Methodology}
This section describes the methodology of the research.

\subsection{Data Collection}
This subsection details how data was collected.

\subsection{Data Analysis}
This subsection explains how the data was analyzed.

\section{Results}
This section presents the results of the research.

\section{Conclusion}
This section concludes the document and summarizes the findings.

\end{document}
```

In the above example, `\documentclass{article}` specifies the document class. The `\tableofcontents` command is placed right after `\begin{document}`. The `\newpage` command is optional and is used here to start the actual content on a new page after the table of contents.

To create the actual structure of the document, commands like `\section`, `\subsection`, and `\subsubsection` are used to organize the content into sections and subsections. LaTeX takes care of numbering these sections and includes them in the table of contents. When you compile this document, LaTeX will first create a `.toc` file with the necessary information for the table of contents, and in subsequent runs, it will use this file to populate the table of contents in the document.

Remember that the table of contents might not appear correctly the first time you compile the document because LaTeX needs at least two compilations: one to gather the information about sections and page numbers, and another to actually place the table of contents in the document with the correct page numbers.

